      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/cou2/relevance-qoi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance Gradation 4 — normalised index of hemolysis directly linked to clinical endpoint",
        "description": "The primary QoI (normalised index of hemolysis, NIH) must be formally linked to the clinical endpoint (plasma free haemoglobin threshold) through a documented physiological model or regulatory precedent. The linkage must be reviewed and accepted by a clinical subject-matter expert."
      },
      "rationale": "NIH is the primary QoI and is formally linked to plasma free haemoglobin thresholds per ASTM F1841 and documented clinical SME review. The QoI is directly relevant to the regulatory decision. Relevance requirement satisfied at Gradation 4."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/relevance-validation-activities",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/cou2/relevance-validation-activities",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation relevance Gradation 4 — validation geometry and operating conditions match COU within documented similarity criteria",
        "description": "The validation experiments must be performed on the same device geometry (or a geometrically similar surrogate with documented similarity rationale) at operating conditions spanning the full COU2 envelope. Similarity criteria (Reynolds number, specific speed, tip speed ratio) must be explicitly documented and met."
      },
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on the FDA generic pump geometry, which matches the COU2 device. However, only three of the five COU2 operating points are covered by the validation dataset; the two highest-flow operating points fall outside the validated envelope. Achieved level is Gradation 3. This gap reduces confidence in extrapolated predictions at the boundary of the operating envelope."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error (iterative convergence, round-off, and floating-point arithmetic errors) is scoped out at COU2 because the solver residuals drop below 1×10⁻⁶ for all conserved variables at all operating points, and double-precision arithmetic is enforced throughout. Solver error is demonstrably negligible relative to discretization error (the dominant numerical uncertainty source assessed under the Discretization error factor) and contributes less than 0.1% to total simulation uncertainty per the Monte Carlo UQ ensemble. Scoping is justified and documented in the UQ report (Morrison et al. 2024, §4.3)."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error is scoped out because all COU2 simulations were executed by a single analyst team following a documented simulation protocol with independent peer review of all boundary condition assignments and post-processing scripts. No manual intervention in solver settings occurred outside the protocol. A formal use-error assessment would require a multi-analyst round-robin study, which is deferred to a future COU3 assessment. The scoping decision is documented in the project quality plan and accepted by the credibility assessment team."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty (turbulence model selection, hemolysis damage model formulation) is scoped out of the structured credibility factor assessment because it is addressed directly through the Output comparison factor: the systematic over-prediction bias documented there subsumes model-form error in the aggregate QoI comparison. A standalone model-form sensitivity study varying turbulence closure (k-ω SST vs. RSM) was performed informally and showed < 4% variation in NIH; results are archived but not formally scored as a separate credibility factor at this assessment stage."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Model input uncertainty (fluid viscosity, density, non-Newtonian parameters, and pump geometry tolerances) is addressed through the Monte Carlo UQ ensemble (500 samples) documented in the UQ report and linked to the ValidationResults. A separate structured credibility factor assessment for model inputs is scoped out because the UQ ensemble already propagates input uncertainty to the QoI and its contribution is captured within the Output comparison factor's combined uncertainty bands. Scoping rationale accepted by the credibility assessment team."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test sample variability (lot-to-lot variation in porcine blood used for bench hemolysis measurements) is scoped out because all bench experiments used a single characterised blood lot with documented haematological parameters, eliminating inter-lot variability as a distinct uncertainty source. Intra-lot variability is captured within the experimental uncertainty bands reported in the Output comparison factor. A multi-lot study is recommended for future submissions but is not required at the current assessment stage given the single-lot design."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/equivalency-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters between simulation and bench experiment is scoped out as a standalone factor because it is fully addressed by the Test conditions factor (Gradation 4 achieved), which documents the traceability of all boundary conditions to measured experimental values. A separate equivalency assessment would be redundant. The scoping decision is noted in the credibility assessment plan."
    }
